e report indicates that none were covered.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing coverage tracking**\\n\\nIt seems dynamic access tracking might only count reflective calls on library classes or under certain conditions with metadata. Maybe my bean classes need specific conditions to reach BeanPropertyWriter, but if it’s not captured in the native build due to a standard writer path? I should have a bean serializer for the public field. Yet, I see it’s uncovered. Could it be that the report only tracks dynamic access inside the library? The generated report shows all 0s, indicating that possibly no tests have run. The previous attempt only covered one, so external workflow must have found none for BeanPropertyWriter.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating serialization issues**\\n\\nI wonder if the test metadata isn't updated for new private classes, which could prevent the native image from accessing them. Even if tests compile, they may fail. I need to consider whether the dynamic-access report is from a JVM agent or static. The current reachability metadata includes public classes but not private ones. The access permissions shouldn't matter, but maybe the issue is that JSON.std.with(FORCE_REFLECTION_ACCESS) isn’t applying correctly. It could be that our classes aren’t being recognized properly when trying to use the bean serializer.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_avuZMgKEFcTNgBeFfsKAARis|fc_01122d506b86142f0169f02de8fd408195875207c662e0ebec", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/com.fasterxml.jackson.jr/jackson-jr-objects/2.21.0/src/test/java/com_fasterxml_jackson_jr/jackson_jr_objects/BeanPropertyWriterDynamicAccessTest.java"}}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_I4xRlAmtdyKnU6AMJRUBcm3D|fc_01122d506b86142f0169f02de8fd508195ae5cbd4c838eafff", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge1/metadata-forge/local_repositories/source_context/com.fasterxml.jackson.jr/jackson-jr-objects/2.21.0/main/e